{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535339"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:54:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:54:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15322"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15322"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.5,0.07,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8013"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109668"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8013"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15322"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92071"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"542"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"1654"},{"type":"tags","id":"6069"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37221"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109668"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three weeks of progressively worsening lower back pain. The pain is severe, constant, and worse at night and with movement. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension. His medications include metformin and perindopril. He has no history of trauma or previous back problems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. He has marked tenderness over the L3/L4 vertebrae with severely restricted spinal movement due to pain. Straight leg raise is negative bilaterally and there are no neurological deficits in the lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 13.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EC-reactive protein 85 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EErythrocyte sedimentation rate 78 mm/hr (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging shows vertebral osteomyelitis at L3/L4 with an epidural abscess causing spinal cord compression.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate empiric antibiotic regimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous ceftriaxone plus vancomycin","Intravenous flucloxacillin, vancomycin, and ceftriaxone","Intravenous ciprofloxacin plus vancomycin","Intravenous flucloxacillin alone","Oral amoxicillin-clavulanate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with vertebral osteomyelitis complicated by epidural abscess requiring urgent surgical intervention. The choice of empiric antibiotics is crucial while awaiting culture results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous flucloxacillin, vancomycin, and ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E provides the most comprehensive empiric coverage for this severe infection. This combination covers methicillin-sensitive and resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MSSA and MRSA) as well as gram-negative organisms, which is appropriate given the severity of infection and presence of epidural abscess in a diabetic patient. Notably, the administration of flucloxacillin and ceftriaxone need to be prioritised for patients because vancomycin is administered via slow infusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone plus vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be an option for patients with nonsevere hypersensitivity to penicillins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E alone would only provide adequate coverage for MSSA but would miss MRSA and gram-negative organisms, which are important considerations in this high-risk patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate for severe infection requiring parenteral therapy and does not provide reliable MRSA coverage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ciprofloxacin plus vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be an option for patients with severe hypersensitivity to penicillins, providing coverage for both gram-positive and gram-negative organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood cultures should be obtained before starting antibiotics to guide targeted therapy. Surgical debridement is indicated given the presence of epidural abscess with cord compression. Duration of antibiotic therapy is typically 6-12 weeks, with transition to oral antibiotics based on clinical response and organism susceptibilities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Empiric antibiotics for vertebral osteomyelitis should cover Staphylococcus aureus as the most common pathogen.","Blood cultures should be obtained before starting antibiotics to guide targeted therapy.","Urgent surgical intervention is required in vertebral osteomyelitis with epidural abscess or neurological compromise."],"references":["Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {14 Nov 2024}. https://www.tg.org.au","Berbari EF, Kanj SS, Kowalski TJ, et al. 2015 Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Native Vertebral Osteomyelitis in Adults. Clin Infect Dis 2015; 61:e26-46. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26229122"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15322"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92071"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-24T13:36:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-24T13:37:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8013"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109668"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"a